#open-question(title: [Can Salivary Metabolomics Distinguish ME/CFS Unrefreshing Sleep from Primary Insomnia?])[
ME/CFS patients report unrefreshing sleep at 91--100% prevalence, yet objective PSG often shows near-normal sleep architecture @Maksoud2021MECFSSleepReview. This subjective-objective disconnect is one of the most puzzling features of the disease.

A study would collect morning saliva samples from n >= 30 ME/CFS patients (stratified by unrefreshing sleep severity on PROMIS Sleep Disturbance), n >= 30 primary insomnia patients, and n >= 30 healthy controls matched for age, sex, and habitual sleep duration. LC-HRMS metabolomic profiling would compare metabolite signatures across groups. Prediction: ME/CFS unrefreshing sleep will show a distinct metabolic fingerprint that differs from both primary insomnia (where sleep is subjectively poor and objectively disrupted) and healthy controls.

*Secondary question:* Does the ME/CFS fingerprint, if present, most closely resemble the Oishi et al. chronic poor-sleep profile (suggesting peripheral sleep disruption) or a novel pattern (suggesting ME/CFS-specific pathophysiology)?

*Control for confounders:* Medication status (SSRIs, SNRIs, anticonvulsants, benzodiazepines, melatonin), salivary flow rate, oral microbiome status, and circadian collection time must be recorded to distinguish sleep-specific signals from medication, autonomic, or circadian artifacts.

*Reference data:* Oishi et al.@Oishi2025ChronicSleepSaliva provides a chronic poor-sleep reference panel (PSQI-defined, 13 metabolites altered, 86.6% classification) from a general population. This is supportive but non-definitive evidence due to cross-sectional design and lack of objective sleep measures.
] <oq:saliva-metabolomics-me-cfs-insomnia>
